Name: Flipper@connerdev: works, but no settings reachable in LM19.1
Comment_Body: Hi @Mintulix,  You can try to edit extension's metadata.json file.   First quit extensions module of Cinnamon settings. Then open metadata.json  `xed ~/.local/share/cinnamon/extensions/Flipper@connerdev/metadata.json`  Add 3.8 and 4.0 lines to metadata.json file, like following link.  https://paste2.org/II7OgvZw

Name: Flipper@connerdev: works, but no settings reachable in LM19.1
Comment_Body: Thanks for your comment, it works now. I tried this before including restarting Cinnamon, but I think I didn't close the extension window. So the whole workaround is this: 1. Deinstall extension (e.g. Flipper), just quit or remove doesn't work (minus sign is deactivated). 2. Install extension again, but don't activate it yet. 3. Add actual Cinnamon version (4.0) to metadata.json (that wasn't necessary before) 4. Close and reopen extension/settings window (and restart Cinnamon?) 5. Activate extension  Should I close this issue? For me it's closed, but for others...?

Name: Extensions licensing
Comment_Body: @germanfr do you want me to go ahead and add the GPL 2.0 to the remaining extensions that don't have a license currently set?

Name: Extensions licensing
Comment_Body: @icarter09 you can't do that. You can only add the respective license to those who have it but don't indicate it in the `info.json` file. Others have GitHub's license by default which does't say you can relicense anything.

Name: Extensions licensing
Comment_Body: @germanfr what would be the fix for this issue concerning the extensions that have no author/maintainer and have no license?

Name: Extensions licensing
Comment_Body: Many of the authors have [donated their xlets](https://github.com/linuxmint/cinnamon-spices-applets/issues/668), and from my understanding, that basically would pass the judgement on copyright maintenance, along with code maintenance to us. A lot of the code is ported from Cinnamon and Gnome Shell extensions, so I think a GPLv2 default makes sense. Take it as a case by case basis, sure, but GPLv2 is the bare minimum any of these should be licensed because Cinnamon is GPLv2. Cinnamon extensions are not linked libraries, they are run in the same context.

Name: [Request] Can we ask for requests here? Also a bug. (opacify@anish.org)
Comment_Body: @RaitaroH Requests are fine. In the future, it will be helpful to include the extension you're making the request for in the issue title, and if you know the author's github name, include it in the description. That way your issue doesn't get lost in the crowd.  @AnishN if you are still interested in developing this extension could you please respond to this request?

Comment_Body: Thank you for the quick response. I will know next time I post.  Hope the extensions and other stuff that was kept on the new spices website to be fixed and have a better overall experience with Cinnamon.   Thank you Linux Mint Team!
